Tommy Duncombe was not only indefatigable at Crockford's , but at every other rendezvous of the votaries of fortune a skilful player withal , and not unfrequently a winner beyond expectation . 
One night at Crockford's he astonished the house by carrying off sixteen hundred pounds . 
Tom Duncombe died poor , but , says his son , rich in the memory of those who esteemed him , as Honest Tom Duncombe . 
But we can hardly fancy , we cannot leave , a son of Duncombe in such a frame of mind . 
We cannot say to HIM Macte nova virtute , puer sic itur ad astra . 
In virtue renewed go on thus to the skies we go . 
We are unfeignedly reluctant to check a filial effusion , or to tell disagreeable truths but there are occasions when a sense of public duty imperatively requires them to be told . 
Why did this exemplary parent die poor ? When did he abandon the allurements of a patrician circle ? He died poor because he wasted a fine fortune . 
If he abandoned a patrician circle , it was because he was tired of it , or thought he could make a better thing of democracy . 
If he conquered his passions , it was , like St Evremond by indulging them . 
Honest Tom Duncombe ! We never heard him so designated before except in pleasantry . 
A ruined spendthrift , although he may have many good qualities , can never , strictly speaking , be termed honest . 
It is absurd to say of him that he is nobody's enemy but his own with family , friends , and tradespeople paying the penalty for his self indulgence . 
There was one quality of honesty , however , which honest Tom Duncombe did possess . 
He was not a hypocrite . 
He was not devoid of right feeling . 
No , he would have said , if he could have anticipated this most ill chosen , however well intentioned , tribute , spare me this terrible irony . 
Do not provoke the inevitable retort . 
This is a terrible rejoinder to a son endeavouring to raise a monument to his beloved and respected parent . 
It was a denunciation of gambling in all its varieties , and was , no doubt , well intentioned . 
